{"id":"quant-ph/9505014","submitter":"John Costella","authors":"John P. Costella (School of Physics, The University of Melbourne)","title":"[p,q] does not equal (i h-bar)","comments":"Standard LaTeX, 6 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":"UM-P-95/51","categories":"quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  In this short note, I point out that [p,q] does not equal (i h-bar), contrary\nto the original claims of Born and Jordan, and Dirac. Rather, [p,q] is equal to\nsomething that is *infinitesimally different* from (i h-bar). While this\ndifference is usually harmless, it does provide the solution of the Born-Jordan\n\"trace paradox\" of [p,q]. More recently, subtleties of a very similar form have\nbeen found to be of fundamental importance in quantum field theory.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 24 May 1995 05:40:43 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
